issue.title: Incorrect description for days of week when using # character
issue.body:
Hi,

I was trying the following expression for quartz: 
```
1 0 0 ? * 1#1 *
```

According to the specification, day of the week should be 1-7. So the above expression should be translated to:
```
At 12:00:01 AM, on the first Sunday of the month
```

But since cronstrue is using an array of days to find the text, that is being translated to 
```
At 12:00:01 AM, on the first Monday of the month
```

And the library is also accepting day of week `0`which is not supported. And it's returning null for day of week `7` which should be Saturday.

issue.title: Incomplete cron expressions with '/' fail silently
issue.body:
cRonstrue treats the incomplete value `/5` as valid, but silently fails to parse it:

```typescript
cronstrue.toString("/5 * * * *", {
  throwExceptionOnParseError: true,
  verbose: true,
  locale: "en",
})
```
produces the string "Every 5 minutes, starting at  minutes past the hour, every hour, every day" - note the double whitespace in front of "minutes".

Expected: throws

Reproduced in versions 2.14.0 and 1.125.0 .

Note: `5/` also does not throw but is silently treated as `5`... that may actually be fair.

issue.title: Incorrect leading zero in 12-hour time
issue.body:
Thanks for all the great work on cRonstrue!

I noticed that when a time in 24-hour format is converted to 12-hour format, it still has a leading zero: `16:51` or `51 16 * * *` becomes `04:51 PM`. The leading zero for hours is used in 24-hour time (e.g., `04:51` for `4:51 AM`) but not in 12-hour time. I would expect `16:51` to be translated as `4:51 PM`.

comment.body:
Hi @jweill-aws - I've seen requests for both formats and I think [ISO 8601](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601) (at least) calls for leading zeros.  Regardless, adding an option for this could be useful.

Related: https://github.com/bradymholt/cRonstrue/issues/217

issue.title: Misleading description when both day of month and day of week is set
issue.body:
Given a cron schedule where both day of month and day of week is set (e.g. `0 0 1-2 * 1-5`) the description is `At 12:00 AM, between day 1 and 2 of the month, Monday through Friday`. This is slightly misleading as the cron schedule will run between day 1 and 2 of the month, _and independently_ will also run every Mon-Fri. 

A better description would include an `and` between the two parts (e.g. https://crontab.guru/#0_0_1-2_*_1-5): `At 12:00 AM, between day 1 and 2 of the month, and Monday through Friday`.

(issue also described in this SO questions: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/37627256/cron-job-to-run-on-a-range-of-days-only-on-a-particular-day-of-week)

issue.title: Incorrect leading zero in 12-hour time
issue.body:
Thanks for all the great work on cRonstrue!

I noticed that when a time in 24-hour format is converted to 12-hour format, it still has a leading zero: `16:51` or `51 16 * * *` becomes `04:51 PM`. The leading zero for hours is used in 24-hour time (e.g., `04:51` for `4:51 AM`) but not in 12-hour time. I would expect `16:51` to be translated as `4:51 PM`.

comment.body:
Hi @jweill-aws - I've seen requests for both formats and I think [ISO 8601](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601) (at least) calls for leading zeros.  Regardless, adding an option for this could be useful.

Related: https://github.com/bradymholt/cRonstrue/issues/217

issue.title: Misleading description when both day of month and day of week is set
issue.body:
Given a cron schedule where both day of month and day of week is set (e.g. `0 0 1-2 * 1-5`) the description is `At 12:00 AM, between day 1 and 2 of the month, Monday through Friday`. This is slightly misleading as the cron schedule will run between day 1 and 2 of the month, _and independently_ will also run every Mon-Fri. 

A better description would include an `and` between the two parts (e.g. https://crontab.guru/#0_0_1-2_*_1-5): `At 12:00 AM, between day 1 and 2 of the month, and Monday through Friday`.

(issue also described in this SO questions: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/37627256/cron-job-to-run-on-a-range-of-days-only-on-a-particular-day-of-week)
